    "definition": "F.8.8 Impact Attenuator Data - IAD"
  },
  "F.8.8.1": {
    "page_number": "47",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.1",
    "definition": "F.8.8.1 All teams must include an Impact Attenuator Data (IAD) report as part of the SES."
  },
  "F.8.8.2": {
    "page_number": "47",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.2",
    "definition": "F.8.8.2 Impact Attenuator Functional Requirements\\nThese are not test requirements\\na. Decelerates the vehicle at a rate not exceeding 20 g average and 40 g peak\\nb. Energy absorbed must be more than 7350 J\\nWhen:\\n• Total mass of Vehicle is 300 kg\\n• Impact velocity is 7.0 m/s"
  },
  "F.8.8.3": {
    "page_number": "47",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.3",
    "definition": "F.8.8.3 When using the Standard Impact Attenuator, the SES must meet the following:\\na. Test data will not be submitted\\nb. All other requirements of this section must be included.\\nc. Photos of the actual attenuator must be included\\nd. Evidence that the Standard IA meets the design criteria provided in the Standard Impact\\nAttenuator specification must be included with the SES. This may be a receipt or packing slip from the supplier."
  },
  "F.8.8.4": {
    "page_number": "47",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.4",
    "definition": "F.8.8.4 The Impact Attenuator Data Report when NOT using the Standard Impact Attenuator must\\ninclude:\\na. Test data that proves that the Impact Attenuator Assembly meets the Functional\\nRequirements F.8.8.2\\nb. Calculations showing how the reported absorbed energy and decelerations have been\\nderived.\\nc. A schematic of the test method.\\nd. Photos of the attenuator, annotated with the height of the attenuator before and after\\ntesting."
  }
}

48:
{
  "F.8.8.5": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.5",
    "definition": "The Impact Attenuator Test is valid for only one Competition Year"
  },
  "F.8.8.6": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.6",
    "definition": "Impact Attenuator Test Setup\na. During any test, the Impact Attenuator must be attached to the Anti Intrusion Plate using\nthe intended vehicle attachment method.\nb. The Impact Attenuator Assembly must be attached to a structurally representative\nsection of the intended chassis.\nThe test fixture must have equivalent strength and stiffness to a baseline front bulkhead.\nA solid block of material in the shape of the front bulkhead is not “structurally\nrepresentative”.\nc. There must be 50 mm minimum clearance rearwards of the Anti Intrusion Plate to the\ntest fixture.\nd. No part of the Anti Intrusion Plate may permanently deflect more than 25 mm beyond\nthe position of the Anti Intrusion Plate before the test.\nThe 25 mm spacing represents the front bulkhead support and insures that the plate does not\nintrude excessively into the cockpit."
  },
  "F.8.8.7": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.7",
    "definition": "Test Conduct\na. Composite Impact Attenuators must be Dynamic Tested.\nOther Impact Attenuator constructions may be Dynamic Tested or Quasi-Static Tested\nb. Dynamic Testing (sled, pendulum, drop tower, etc.) of the Impact Attenuator must be\nconducted at a dedicated test facility. This facility may be part of the University, but must\nbe supervised by professional staff or the University faculty. Teams must not construct\ntheir own dynamic test apparatus.\nc. Quasi-Static Testing may be performed by teams using their University’s\nfacilities/equipment, but teams are advised to exercise due care when performing all\ntests."
  },
  "F.8.8.8": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.8.8.8",
    "definition": "Test Analysis\na. When using acceleration data from the dynamic test, the average deceleration must be\ncalculated based on the raw unfiltered data.\nb. If peaks above the 40 g limit are present in the data, a Channel Filter Class (CFC) 60\n(100Hz) filter per SAE Recommended Practice J211 “Instrumentation for Impact Test”, or\na 100 Hz, 3rd order, low pass Butterworth (-3dB at 100 Hz) filter may be applied."
  },
  "F.9": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.9",
    "definition": "FUEL SYSTEM (IC ONLY)\nFuel System Location and Protection are subject to approval during SES review and Technical\nInspection."
  },
  "F.9.1": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.9.1",
    "definition": "Location"
  },
  "F.9.1.1": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.9.1.1",
    "definition": "Any portion of the Fuel System that is less than 350 mm above the ground, and all parts of the\nFuel Tank, must be inside the Primary Structure (F.1.10)."
  },
  "F.9.1.2": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.9.1.2",
    "definition": "In side view, any portion of the Fuel System must not project below the lower surface of the\nchassis"
  },
  "F.9.2": {
    "page_number": "48",
    "rule_number": "F.9.2",
    "definition": "Protection\nAll Fuel Tanks must be shielded from side or rear impact"
  }
}

49:
{
  "F.10.1.1": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.1.1",
    "definition": "All Accumulator Containers must be:\na. Designed to withstand forces from deceleration in all directions\nb. Made from a Nonflammable Material ( F.1.18 )"
  },
  "F.10.1.2": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.1.2",
    "definition": "Design of the Accumulator Container must be documented in the SES.\nDocumentation includes materials used, drawings/images, fastener locations, cell/segment\nweight and cell/segment position."
  },
  "F.10.1.3": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.1.3",
    "definition": "The Accumulator Containers and mounting systems are subject to approval during SES review\nand Technical Inspection"
  },
  "F.10.1.4": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.1.4",
    "definition": "If the Accumulator Container is not constructed from steel or aluminum, the material properties should be established at a temperature of 60°C"
  },
  "F.10.1.5": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.1.5",
    "definition": "If adhesives are used for credited bonding, the bond performance should be established at a temperature of 60°C"
  },
  "F.10.2.1": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.2.1",
    "definition": "The Floor or Bottom must be made from one of the three:\na. Steel 1.25 mm minimum thickness\nb. Aluminum 3.2 mm minimum thickness\nc. Equivalent Alternate / Composite materials ( F.4.1, F.4.3 )"
  },
  "F.10.2.2": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.2.2",
    "definition": "Vertical Walls, Covers and Lids must be made from one of the three:\na. Steel 0.9 mm minimum thickness\nb. Aluminum 2.3 mm minimum thickness\nc. Equivalent Alternate / Composite materials ( F.4.1, F.4.3 )"
  },
  "F.10.2.3": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.2.3",
    "definition": "The accepted methods of joining walls to walls and walls to floor are:\na. Welding\n• Welds may be continuous or interrupted.\n• If interrupted, the weld/space ratio must be 1:1 or higher\n• All weld lengths must be more than 25 mm\nb. Fasteners\nCombined strength of the fasteners must be Equivalent to the strength of the welded\njoint ( F.10.2.3.a above )\nc. Bonding\n• Bonding must meet F.5.5\n• Strength of the bonded joint must be Equivalent to the strength of the welded joint\n( F.10.2.3.a above )\n• Bonds must run the entire length of the joint"
  },
  "F.10.2.4": {
    "page_number": "49",
    "rule_number": "F.10.2.4",
    "definition": "Covers and Lids must be attached with a minimum of one fastener F.10.2.3.b for each external\nvertical wall per section"
  }
}

51:
{
  "F.10.5.1": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.1",
    "definition": "Attachment of the Accumulator Container must be documented in the SES"
  },
  "F.10.5.2": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.2",
    "definition": "Accumulator Containers must:\n a. Attach to the Major Structure of the chassis\n A maximum of two attachment points may be on a chassis tube between two\n triangulated nodes.\n b. Not attach to the Shoulder Harness Mounting"
  },
  "F.10.5.3": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.3",
    "definition": "Any fasteners used to attach Accumulator Container(s) are Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2"
  },
  "F.10.5.4": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.4",
    "definition": "Each fastened attachment point to a composite Accumulator Container requires backing plates that are one of the two:\n a. Steel with a thickness of 2 mm minimum\n b. Alternate materials Equivalent to 2 mm thickness steel"
  },
  "F.10.5.5": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.5",
    "definition": "Teams must justify the Accumulator Container attachment using one of the two methods:\n• Corner Attachments and Analysis per F.10.5.6 and F.10.5.8\n• Load Based Analysis per F.10.5.7 and F.10.5.8"
  },
  "F.10.5.6": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.6",
    "definition": "Accumulator Attachment – Corner Attachments\na. Eight or more attachments are required for any configuration.\n• One attachment for each corner of a rectangular structure of multiple Accumulator\nSegments\n• More than the minimum number of fasteners may be required for non rectangular\narrangements\nExamples: If not filled in with additional structure, an extruded L shape would require\nattachments at 10 convex corners (the corners at the inside of the L are not convex);\nan extruded hexagon would require 12 attachments\nb. The mechanical connections at each corner must be 50 mm or less from the corner of\nthe Segment\nc. Each attachment point must be able to withstand a Test Load equal to 1/4 of total mass\nof the container accelerating at 40 g"
  },
  "F.10.5.7": {
    "page_number": "51",
    "rule_number": "F.10.5.7",
    "definition": "Accumulator Attachment – Load Based\na. The minimum number of attachment points depends on the total mass of the container:\nAccumulator Weight Minimum Attachment Points\n< 20 kg 4\n20 – 30 kg 6\n30 – 40 kg 8\n> 40 kg 10\nb. Each attachment point, including any brackets, backing plates and inserts, must be able\nto withstand 15 kN minimum in any direction"
  }
}

53:
{
  "F.11.2.3": {
    "page_number": "53",
    "rule_number": "F.11.2.3",
    "definition": "F.11.2.3 All Non Crushable Items should have a minimum 25 mm clearance to the surface of the Accumulator Container.\\nNon Crushable Items include, but are not limited to motors, differentials, and the side or rear impact structure itself. Accumulator mounts do not require clearance"
  },
  "F.11.2.4": {
    "page_number": "53",
    "rule_number": "F.11.2.4",
    "definition": "F.11.2.4 Non Crushable Items mounted behind the Rear Impact structure must not be able to come through the Rear Impact structure."
  }
}

54:
Lookup Table for Rules:
{
  "T.1": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1",
    "definition": "COCKPIT"
  },
  "T.1.1": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1.1",
    "definition": "Cockpit Opening"
  },
  "T.1.1.1": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1.1.1",
    "definition": "The template shown below must pass through the cockpit opening"
  },
  "T.1.1.2": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1.1.2",
    "definition": "The template will be held horizontally, parallel to the ground, and inserted vertically from a height above any Primary Structure or bodywork that is between the Front Hoop and the Main Hoop until it meets both of: ( refer to F.6.4 and F.7.5.1 ) a. Has passed 25 mm below the lowest point of the top of the Side Impact Structure b. Is less than or equal to 320 mm above the lowest point inside the cockpit"
  },
  "T.1.1.3": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1.1.3",
    "definition": "Fore and aft translation of the template is permitted during insertion."
  },
  "T.1.1.4": {
    "page_number": "54",
    "rule_number": "T.1.1.4",
    "definition": "During this test:\na. The steering wheel, steering column, seat and all padding may be removed\nb. The shifter, shift mechanism, or clutch mechanism must not be removed unless it is integral with the steering wheel and is removed with the steering wheel\nc. The firewall must not be moved or removed\nd. Cables, wires, hoses, tubes, etc. must not block movement of the template\nDuring inspection, the steering column, for practical purposes, will not be removed. The template may be maneuvered around the steering column, but not any fixed supports.\nFor ease of use, the template may contain a slot at the front center that the steering column may pass through."
  }
}

56:
{
  "T.1.3.2": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.3.2",
    "definition": "While the driver’s feet are touching the pedals, in side and front views, any part of the driver’s feet or legs must not extend above or outside of the Major Structure of the Chassis."
  },
  "T.1.3.3": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.3.3",
    "definition": "All moving suspension and steering components and other sharp edges inside the cockpit\nbetween the Front Hoop and a vertical plane 100 mm rearward of the pedals must be covered\nby a shield made of a solid material.\nMoving components include, but are not limited to springs, shock absorbers, rocker arms, anti-\nroll/sway bars, steering racks and steering column CV joints."
  },
  "T.1.3.4": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.3.4",
    "definition": "Covers over suspension and steering components must be removable to allow inspection of\nthe mounting points"
  },
  "T.1.4.1": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.4.1",
    "definition": "Accelerator Pedal\na. An Accelerator Pedal must control the Powertrain output\nb. Pedal Travel is the percent of travel from a fully released position to a fully applied\nposition. 0% is fully released and 100% is fully applied.\nc. The Accelerator Pedal must:\n• Return to 0% Pedal Travel when not pushed\n• Have a positive stop to prevent any cable, actuation system or sensor from damage\nor overstress"
  },
  "T.1.4.2": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.4.2",
    "definition": "Any mechanism in the throttle system that could become jammed must be covered.\nThis is to prevent debris or interference and includes but is not limited to a gear mechanism"
  },
  "T.1.4.3": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.4.3",
    "definition": "All Vehicle Controls (steering, gear change, Cockpit Main Switch / Cockpit Shutdown Button)\nmust be operated from inside the cockpit without any part of the driver, including hands, arms\nor elbows, being outside of:\na. The Side Impact Structure defined in F.6.4 / F.7.5\nb. Two longitudinal vertical planes parallel to the centerline of the chassis touching the\nuppermost member of the Side Impact Structure"
  },
  "T.1.4.4": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.4.4",
    "definition": "All Vehicle Controls must stay below the top-most point of the Front Hoop in any operational\nposition"
  },
  "T.1.5.1": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.5.1",
    "definition": "The Driver’s Seat must be protected by one of the following:\na. In side view, the lowest point of any Driver’s Seat must be no lower than the upper\nsurface of the lowest structural tube or equivalent\nb. A longitudinal tube (or tubes) that meets the requirements for Side Impact tubing\n(F.3.2.1.e), passing underneath the lowest point of the Driver Seat."
  },
  "T.1.6.1": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.6.1",
    "definition": "When seated in the normal driving position, sufficient heat insulation must be provided to\nensure that the driver will not contact any metal or other materials which may become heated\nto a surface temperature above 60°C."
  },
  "T.1.6.2": {
    "page_number": "56",
    "rule_number": "T.1.6.2",
    "definition": "Insulation may be external to the cockpit or incorporated with the Driver’s Seat or Firewall."
  }
}

57:
{
  "T.1.6.3": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.6.3",
    "definition": "The design must address all three types of heat transfer between the heat source (examples\ninclude but are not limited to: exhaust pipe, coolant hose/tube, Accumulator Container) and\nthe panel that the driver could contact (seat or floor):\na. Conduction Isolation by one of the following:\n• No direct contact between the heat source and the panel\n• A heat resistant, conduction isolation material with a minimum thickness of 8 mm\nb. Convection Isolation by a minimum air gap of 25 mm between the heat source and the\npanel\nc. Radiation Isolation by one of the following:\n• A solid metal heat shield with a minimum thickness of 0.4 mm\n• Reflective foil or tape when combined with conduction insulation"
  },
  "T.1.7": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.7",
    "definition": "Floor Closeout"
  },
  "T.1.7.1": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.7.1",
    "definition": "All vehicles must have a Floor Closeout to prevent track debris from entering"
  },
  "T.1.7.2": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.7.2",
    "definition": "The Floor Closeout must extend from the foot area to the firewall"
  },
  "T.1.7.3": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.7.3",
    "definition": "The panel(s) must be made of a solid, non brittle material"
  },
  "T.1.7.4": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.7.4",
    "definition": "If multiple panels are used, gaps between panels must not exceed 3 mm"
  },
  "T.1.8": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8",
    "definition": "Firewall(s)"
  },
  "T.1.8.1": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8.1",
    "definition": "Requirement\nA Firewall(s) must separate the driver compartment and any portion of the Driver Harness from:\na. All components of the Fuel System, the engine oil, the liquid cooling systems, any lithium\nb. batteries\nb. (EV only) All Tractive System components other than Outboard Wheel Motors EV.4.1.3\nwhere mounted at the wheels or on the front control arms"
  },
  "T.1.8.2": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8.2",
    "definition": "Construction\nAny Firewall must:\na. Be a non permeable surface made from a rigid, Nonflammable Material\nb. Seal completely against the passage of fluids (the Firewall itself, edges, any pass throughs and Floor Closeout)\nc. Be rigidly mounted"
  },
  "T.1.8.3": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8.3",
    "definition": "Positioning\nThe Firewall must extend sufficiently far upwards and/or rearwards and/or sideways where\nany point on the drivers body less than 100 mm above the bottom of the helmet of the tallest\ndriver must not be in direct line of sight with any part given in T.1.8.1 above"
  },
  "T.1.8.4": {
    "page_number": "57",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8.4",
    "definition": "Details\na. Firewalls composed of multiple panels must overlap and be sealed at the joints\nSealing between firewalls must not be a stressed part of the Firewall\nb. Grommets must be used to seal any pass through for wiring, cables, etc"
  }
}

58:
{
  "T.1.8.5": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.1.8.5",
    "definition": "Accumulator Container must not be part of the Firewall"
  },
  "T.1.9": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.1.9",
    "definition": "Tractive System Firewalls (EV Only)"
  },
  "T.1.9.1": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.1.9.1",
    "definition": "Tractive System Firewalls must meet the requirements of T.1.8 above"
  },
  "T.1.9.2": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.1.9.2",
    "definition": "Tractive System Firewalls must be:\na. Made of aluminum\nb. Grounded, refer to EV.6.7 Grounding"
  },
  "T.2": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2",
    "definition": "DRIVER ACCOMMODATION"
  },
  "T.2.1": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.1",
    "definition": "Harness Definitions\na. 5 Point Harness – consists of two Lap Belts, two Shoulder Belts and one Anti-Submarine Belt.\nb. 6 Point Harness – consists of two Lap Belts, two Shoulder Belts and two leg or Anti-Submarine Belts.\nc. 7 Point Harness – consists of two Lap Belts, two Shoulder Belts, two leg or Anti-Submarine Belts and a negative g or Z Belt.\nd. Upright Driving Position - with a seat back angled at 30° or less from the vertical as measured along the line joining the two 200 mm circles of the template of the 95th percentile male as defined in F.5.6.4 and positioned per F.5.6.5\ne. Reclined Driving Position - with a seat back angled at more than 30° from the vertical as measured along the line joining the two 200 mm circles of the template of the 95th percentile male as defined in F.5.6.4 and positioned per F.5.6.5\nf. Chest to Groin Line - the straight line that in side view follows the line of the Shoulder Belts from the chest to the release buckle."
  },
  "T.2.2": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2",
    "definition": "Harness Specification"
  },
  "T.2.2.1": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must use a 5, 6 or 7 Point Harness meeting one or more of the following:\na. SFI Specification 16.1\nb. SFI Specification 16.5\nc. FIA specification 8853/2016"
  },
  "T.2.2.2": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.2",
    "definition": "The belts must have the original manufacturers labels showing the specification and expiration date"
  },
  "T.2.2.3": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.3",
    "definition": "The Harness must be in or before the year of expiration shown on the labels. Harnesses expiring on or before Dec 31 of the calendar year of the competition are permitted."
  },
  "T.2.2.4": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.4",
    "definition": "The Harness must be in new or like new condition, with no signs of wear, cuts, chaffing or other issues"
  },
  "T.2.2.5": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.5",
    "definition": "All Harness hardware must be installed and threaded in accordance with manufacturer’s instructions"
  },
  "T.2.2.6": {
    "page_number": "58",
    "rule_number": "T.2.2.6",
    "definition": "All Harness hardware must be used as received from the manufacturer. No modification (including drilling, cutting, grinding, etc) is permitted."
  }
}

59:
{
  "T.2.3.1": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.3.1",
    "definition": "Vehicles with a Reclined Driving Position must have:\na. A 6 Point Harness or a 7 Point Harness\nb. Anti-Submarine Belts with tilt lock adjusters (“quick adjusters”) OR two sets of Anti-\nSubmarine Belts installed."
  },
  "T.2.3.2": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.3.2",
    "definition": "All Lap Belts must incorporate a tilt lock adjuster (“quick adjuster”).\nLap Belts with “pull-up” adjusters are recommended over “pull-down” adjusters."
  },
  "T.2.3.3": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.3.3",
    "definition": "The Shoulder Belts must be the over the shoulder type. Only separate shoulder straps are\npermitted. “Y” type shoulder straps are not allowed. The “H” type configuration is allowed."
  },
  "T.2.4.1": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.4.1",
    "definition": "The Lap Belt, Shoulder Belts and Anti-Submarine Belt(s) must be securely mounted to the\nPrimary Structure."
  },
  "T.2.4.2": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.4.2",
    "definition": "Any guide or support for the belts must be material meeting F.3.2.1.j"
  },
  "T.2.4.3": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.4.3",
    "definition": "Each tab or bracket to which any part of the Harness is attached must:\na. Support a minimum load in pullout and tearout before failure of:\n• If one belt is attached to the tab or bracket 15 kN\n• If two belts are attached to the tab or bracket 30 kN\nb. Be 1.6 mm minimum thickness\nc. Not be in bending when the attached part of the Harness is put under load\nd. Not cause abrasion to the belt webbing"
  },
  "T.2.4.4": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.4.4",
    "definition": "Attachment of tabs or brackets must meet the following:\na. Where brackets are fastened to the chassis, no less than two 6 mm or 1/4” minimum\ndiameter Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2 or stronger must be used to attach the bracket to\nthe chassis.\nb. Where a single shear tab is welded to the chassis, the tab to tube welding must be on\nboth sides of the base of the tab.\nDouble shear attachments are preferred. Tabs and brackets for double shear mounts should\nbe welded on both sides."
  },
  "T.2.4.5": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.4.5",
    "definition": "Harness installation must meet T.1.8.1"
  },
  "T.2.5.1": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.1",
    "definition": "The Lap Belts must pass around the pelvic area below the Anterior Superior Iliac Spines (the\nhip bones)"
  },
  "T.2.5.2": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.2",
    "definition": "Installation of the Lap Belts must go in a straight line from the mounting point until they reach\nthe driver's body without touching any hole in the seat or any other intermediate structure"
  },
  "T.2.5.3": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.3",
    "definition": "The seat must be rolled or grommeted where the Belts or Harness pass through a hole in the\nseat"
  },
  "T.2.5.4": {
    "page_number": "59",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.4",
    "definition": "With an Upright Driving Position:\na. The Lap Belt Side View Angle must be between 45° and 65° to the horizontal.\nb. The centerline of the Lap Belt at the seat bottom should be between 0 – 75 mm forward\nof the seat back to seat bottom junction."
  }
}

60:
{
  "T.2.5.5": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.5",
    "definition": "With a Reclined Driving Position, the Lap Belt Side View Angle must be between 60° and 80° to the horizontal."
  },
  "T.2.5.6": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.6",
    "definition": "The Lap Belts must attach by one of the two:\na. Bolt or eyebolt through a welded tu b e in s e r t o r tested monocoque attachment F . 7 . 9\nb. Bolt or clip to a tab or bracket ( T.2.4.3 ) on a tube frame"
  },
  "T.2.5.7": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.7",
    "definition": "In side view, the Lap Belt must be capable of pivoting freely by using a shouldered bolt or an eye bolt attachment"
  },
  "T.2.5.8": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.5.8",
    "definition": "Any bolt used to attach a Lap Belt, directly to the chassis or to an intermediate bracket, is a Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2, with a minimum diameter that is the smaller of:\n• The bolt diameter specified by the manufacturer\n• 10 mm or 3/8”"
  },
  "T.2.6.1": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.6.1",
    "definition": "From the driver’s shoulders rearwards to the mounting point or structural guide, the Shoulder Belt Side View Angle must be between 10° above the horizontal and 20° below the horizontal."
  },
  "T.2.6.2": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.6.2",
    "definition": "The Shoulder Belt Mount Spacing must be between 175 mm and 235 mm, center to center"
  },
  "T.2.6.3": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.6.3",
    "definition": "The Shoulder Belts must attach by one of the four:\na. Wrap around the Shoulder Harness Mounting bar\nb. Bolt through a welded tube insert or tested monocoque attachment F.7.9\nc. Bolt or clip to a tab or bracket ( T.2.4.3 ) on the Shoulder Harness Mounting bar\nd. Wrap around physically tested hardware attached to a monocoque"
  },
  "T.2.6.4": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.6.4",
    "definition": "Any bolt used to attach a Shoulder Belt, directly to the chassis or to an intermediate bracket, is a Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2, with a minimum diameter that is the smaller of:\n• The bolt diameter specified by the manufacturer\n• 10 mm or 3/8”"
  },
  "T.2.7.1": {
    "page_number": "60",
    "rule_number": "T.2.7.1",
    "definition": "The Anti-Submarine Belt of a 5 point harness must be mounted with the mounting point in line with or slightly forward of the driver’s Chest to Groin Line with an Anti-Submarine Belt Side View Angle no more than 20°"
  }
}

61:
{
  "T.2.7.2": {
    "page_number": "61",
    "rule_number": "T.2.7.2",
    "definition": "The Anti-Submarine Belts of a 6 point harness must be mounted in one of the following ways:\n a. With the belts going vertically down from the groin, or with an Anti-Submarine Belt Side\nView Angle up to 20° rearwards. The Anti-Submarine Belt Mount Spacing should be\napproximately 100 mm apart.\n b. With the Anti-Submarine Belt Mounting Points on the Primary Structure at or near the\nLap Belt anchorages, the driver sitting on the Anti-Submarine Belts, and the belts coming\nup around the groin to the release buckle."
  },
  "T.2.7.3": {
    "page_number": "61",
    "rule_number": "T.2.7.3",
    "definition": "Installation of all Anti-Submarine Belts must go in a straight line from the Anti-Submarine Belt Mounting Point(s) without touching any hole in the seat or any other intermediate structure until they reach:\n a. The release buckle for the 5 Point Harness mounting per T.2.7.1\n b. The first point where the belt touches the driver’s body for the 6 Point Harness mounting per T.2.7.2"
  },
  "T.2.7.4": {
    "page_number": "61",
    "rule_number": "T.2.7.4",
    "definition": "The Anti Submarine Belts must attach by one of the three:\n a. Bolt or eyebolt through a welded tube insert or tested monocoque attachment F.7.9\n b. Bolt or clip to a tab or bracket ( T.2.4.3 ) on a tube frame"
  }
}

62:
{
  "T.2.7.5": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.7.5",
    "definition": "Any bolt used to attach an Anti-Submarine Belt, directly to the chassis or to an intermediate bracket, is a Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2, with a minimum diameter that is the smaller of:\n• The bolt diameter specified by the manufacturer\n• 8 mm or 5/16”"
  },
  "T.2.8": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8",
    "definition": "Head Restraint\nA Head Restraint must be provided to limit the rearward motion of the driver’s head."
  },
  "T.2.8.1": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.1",
    "definition": "A Head Restraint must be provided to limit the rearward motion of the driver’s head."
  },
  "T.2.8.2": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.2",
    "definition": "The Head Restraint must be vertical or near vertical in side view."
  },
  "T.2.8.3": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.3",
    "definition": "All material and structure of the Head Restraint must be inside one or both of:\na. Rollover Protection Envelope F.1.13\nb. Head Restraint Protection (if used) F.5.10"
  },
  "T.2.8.4": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.4",
    "definition": "The Head Restraint, attachment and mounting must be strong enough to withstand a\nminimum force of:\na. 900 N applied in a rearward direction\nb. 300 N applied in a lateral or vertical direction"
  },
  "T.2.8.5": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.5",
    "definition": "For all drivers, the Head Restraint must be located and adjusted where:\na. The Head Restraint is no more than 25 mm away from the back of the driver’s helmet,\nwith the driver in their normal driving position.\nb. The contact point of the back of the driver’s helmet on the Head Restraint is no less than\n50 mm from any edge of the Head Restraint.\nApproximately 100 mm of longitudinal adjustment should accommodate range of specified\ndrivers. Several Head Restraints with different thicknesses may be used"
  },
  "T.2.8.6": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.8.6",
    "definition": "The Head Restraint padding must:\na. Be an energy absorbing material that is one of the two:\n• Meets SFI Spec 45.2\n• CONFOR CF45 (Blue) or CONFOR CF45M (Blue) FIA Technical List No 17\nb. Have a minimum thickness of 38 mm\nc. Have a minimum width of 15 cm\nd. Meet one of the following:\n• minimum area of 235 cm2 AND minimum total height adjustment of 17.5 cm\n• minimum height of 28 cm\ne. Be covered with a thin, flexible material that contains a ~20 mm diameter inspection\nhole in a surface other than the front surface"
  },
  "T.2.9": {
    "page_number": "62",
    "rule_number": "T.2.9",
    "definition": "Roll Bar Padding\nAny portion of the roll bar, roll bar bracing or Chassis which might be contacted by the driver’s\nhelmet must be covered with a minimum thickness of 12 mm of padding which meets SFI Spec\n45.1 or FIA 8857-2001."
  }
}

63:
{
  "T.3.1.1": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must have a Brake System"
  },
  "T.3.1.2": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.2",
    "definition": "The Brake System must:\na. Act on all four wheels\nb. Be operated by a single control\nc. Be capable of locking all four wheels"
  },
  "T.3.1.3": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.3",
    "definition": "The Brake System must have two independent hydraulic circuits\nA leak or failure at any point in the Brake System must maintain effective brake power on\nminimum two wheels"
  },
  "T.3.1.4": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.4",
    "definition": "Each hydraulic circuit must have its own fluid reserve using separate reservoirs or an OEM\nstyle reservoir"
  },
  "T.3.1.5": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.5",
    "definition": "A single brake acting on a limited slip differential may be used"
  },
  "T.3.1.6": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.6",
    "definition": "“Brake by Wire” systems are prohibited"
  },
  "T.3.1.7": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.7",
    "definition": "Unarmored plastic brake lines are prohibited"
  },
  "T.3.1.8": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.8",
    "definition": "The Brake System must be protected with scatter shields from failure of the drive train (see\nT.5.2) or from minor collisions."
  },
  "T.3.1.9": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.9",
    "definition": "In side view any portion of the Brake System that is mounted on the sprung part of the vehicle\nmust not project below the lower surface of the chassis"
  },
  "T.3.1.10": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.10",
    "definition": "Fasteners in the Brake System are Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2"
  },
  "T.3.2.1": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.2.1",
    "definition": "The Brake Pedal must be one of:\n• Fabricated from steel or aluminum\n• Machined from steel, aluminum or titanium"
  },
  "T.3.2.2": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.2.2",
    "definition": "The Brake Pedal and associated components design must withstand a minimum force of 2000\nN without any failure of the Brake System, pedal box, chassis mounting, or pedal adjustment\nThis is not a design criteria. The Brake Pedal and Brake System may be tested by pressing the\npedal with the maximum force that can be exerted by any official when seated normally"
  },
  "T.3.2.3": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.2.3",
    "definition": "Failure of non-loadbearing components in the Brake System or pedal box must not interfere\nwith Brake Pedal operation or Brake System function"
  },
  "T.3.2.4": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.2.4",
    "definition": "(EV only) Additional requirements for Electric Vehicles:\na. The first 90% of the Brake Pedal travel may be used to regenerate energy without\nactuating the hydraulic brake system.\nb. The remaining Brake Pedal travel must directly actuate the hydraulic brake system.\nBrake energy regeneration may stay active."
  },
  "T.3.3.1": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.3.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must have a Brake Over Travel Switch (BOTS). Brake pedal travel exceeding the\nnormal range will actuate the switch"
  },
  "T.3.3.2": {
    "page_number": "63",
    "rule_number": "T.3.3.2",
    "definition": "The BOTS must be a mechanical single pole, single throw (commonly known as a two position)\nswitch (push-pull or flip type)."
  }
}

64:
{
  "Lookup Table for Rules": {
    "T.3.3.3": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.3.3",
      "definition": "Operation of the BOTS to the OFF position must Open the Shutdown Circuit IC.9.2.2 / EV.7.2.2"
    },
    "T.3.3.4": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.3.4",
      "definition": "Repeated operation of the switch must not reset or restore power"
    },
    "T.3.3.5": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.3.5",
      "definition": "The driver must not be able to reset the BOTS."
    },
    "T.3.3.6": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.3.6",
      "definition": "The BOTS must be implemented with analog components, and not using programmable logic controllers, engine control units, or similar functioning digital controllers."
    },
    "T.3.4": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.4",
      "definition": "Brake Light"
    },
    "T.3.4.1": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.4.1",
      "definition": "The vehicle must have a Brake Light that is clearly visible from the rear in very bright sunlight."
    },
    "T.3.4.2": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.4.2",
      "definition": "The Brake Light must be:\na. Red in color on a Black background\nb. Rectangular, triangular or near round shape with a minimum shining surface of 15 cm2\nc. Mounted between the wheel centerline and driver’s shoulder level vertically and\napproximately on vehicle centerline laterally."
    },
    "T.3.4.3": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.4.3",
      "definition": "When LED lights are used without a diffuser, they must not be more than 20 mm apart."
    },
    "T.3.4.4": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.3.4.4",
      "definition": "If a single line of LEDs is used, the minimum length is 150 mm."
    },
    "T.4": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4",
      "definition": "ELECTRONIC THROTTLE COMPONENTS"
    },
    "T.4.1": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.1",
      "definition": "Applicability\nThis section T.4 applies only for:\n• IC vehicles using Electronic Throttle Control (ETC) IC.4\n• EV vehicles"
    },
    "T.4.2": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2",
      "definition": "Accelerator Pedal Position Sensor - APPS"
    },
    "T.4.2.1": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2.1",
      "definition": "The Accelerator Pedal must actuate the APPS T.1.4.1\na. Two springs must be used to return the foot pedal to 0% Pedal Travel\nb. Each spring must be capable of returning the pedal to 0% Pedal Travel with the other\ndisconnected. The springs in the APPS are not acceptable pedal return springs."
    },
    "T.4.2.2": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2.2",
      "definition": "Two or more electrically separate sensors must be used as APPSs. A single OEM type APPS\nwith two completely separate sensors in a single housing is acceptable."
    },
    "T.4.2.3": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2.3",
      "definition": "The APPS sensors must have different transfer functions which meet one of the two:\n• Each sensor has different gradients and/or offsets to the other(s). The circuit must have\na pull-up or pull-down resistor to bring an open circuit input to 0% Pedal Travel\n• An OEM pedal sensor with opposite slopes. Non OEM opposite slope sensor\nconfigurations require prior approval.\nThe intent is that in a short circuit the APPSs will only agree at 0% Pedal Travel"
    },
    "T.4.2.4": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2.4",
      "definition": "Implausibility is defined as a deviation of more than 10% Pedal Travel between the sensors or\nother failure as defined in this Section T.4.2. Use of values larger than 10% Pedal Travel\nrequire justification in the ETC Systems Form and may not be approved"
    },
    "T.4.2.5": {
      "page_number": "64",
      "rule_number": "T.4.2.5",
      "definition": "If an Implausibility occurs between the values of the APPSs and persists for more than 100\nmsec, the power to the (IC) Electronic Throttle / (EV) Motor(s) must be immediately stopped\ncompletely."
    }
  }
}

65:
{
  "T.4.2.6": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.6",
    "definition": "If three sensors are used, then in the case of an APPS failure, any two sensors that agree within 10% Pedal Travel may be used to define the (IC) throttle position / (EV) torque target and the 3rd APPS may be ignored."
  },
  "T.4.2.7": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.7",
    "definition": "Each APPS must be able to be checked during Technical Inspection by having one of the two:\n• A separate detachable connector that enables a check of functions by unplugging it\n• An inline switchable breakout box available that allows disconnection of each APPS signal."
  },
  "T.4.2.8": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.8",
    "definition": "The APPS signals must be sent directly to a controller using an analogue signal or via a digital data transmission bus such as CAN or FlexRay."
  },
  "T.4.2.9": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.9",
    "definition": "Any failure of the APPS or APPS wiring must be detectable by the controller and must be treated like an Implausibility, see T.4.2.4 above."
  },
  "T.4.2.10": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.10",
    "definition": "When an analogue signal is used, the APPS will be considered to have failed when they achieve an open circuit or short circuit condition which generates a signal outside of the normal operating range, for example <0.5 V or >4.5 V.\nThe circuitry used to evaluate the sensor must use pull down or pull up resistors to ensure that open circuit signals result in a failure being detected."
  },
  "T.4.2.11": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.11",
    "definition": "When any kind of digital data transmission is used to transmit the APPS signal,\n a. The ETC Systems Form must contain a detailed description of all the potential failure modes that can occur, the strategy that is used to detect these failures and the tests that have been conducted to prove that the detection strategy works.\n b. The failures to be considered must include but are not limited to the failure of the APPS, APPS signals being out of range, corruption of the message and loss of messages and the associated time outs."
  },
  "T.4.2.12": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.2.12",
    "definition": "The current rules are written to only apply to the APPS (pedal), but the integrity of the torque command signal is important in all stages."
  },
  "T.4.3.1": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.3.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must have a sensor or switch to measure brake pedal position or brake system pressure."
  },
  "T.4.3.2": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.3.2",
    "definition": "The BSE must be able to be checked during Technical Inspection by having one of:\n• A separate detachable connector(s) for any BSE signal(s) to the main ECU without affecting any other connections\n• An inline switchable breakout box available that allows disconnection of each BSE signal(s) to the main ECU without affecting any other connections."
  },
  "T.4.3.3": {
    "page_number": "65",
    "rule_number": "T.4.3.3",
    "definition": "The BSE or switch signals must be sent directly to a controller using an analogue signal or via a digital data transmission bus such as CAN or FlexRay\nAny failure of the BSE or BSE wiring that persists more than 100 msec must be detectable by the controller and treated like an implausibility and power to the (IC) electronic throttle / (EV) Motor(s) must be immediately stopped completely.\n(EV only) It is not necessary to completely deactivate the Tractive System, the motor controller(s) stopping power to the motor(s) is sufficient."
  }
}

66:
{
  "T.4.3.4": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.4.3.4",
    "definition": "When an analogue signal is used, the BSE sensors will be considered to have failed when they achieve an open circuit or short circuit condition which generates a signal outside of the normal operating range, for example <0.5 V or >4.5 V.\nThe circuitry used to evaluate the sensor must use pull down or pull up resistors to ensure\nthat open circuit signals result in a failure being detected."
  },
  "T.4.3.5": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.4.3.5",
    "definition": "When any kind of digital data transmission is used to transmit the BSE signal:\na. The ETC Systems Form must contain a detailed description of all the potential failure modes that can occur, the strategy that is used to detect these failures and the tests that have been conducted to prove that the detection strategy works.\nb. The failures modes must include but are not limited to the failure of the sensor, sensor signals being out of range, corruption of the message and loss of messages and the associated time outs.\nc. In all cases a sensor failure must immediately shutdown power to the motor(s)."
  },
  "T.5": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5",
    "definition": "POWERTRAIN"
  },
  "T.5.1": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.1",
    "definition": "Transmission and Drive\nAny transmission and drivetrain may be used."
  },
  "T.5.2": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2",
    "definition": "Drivetrain Shields and Guards"
  },
  "T.5.2.1": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.1",
    "definition": "Exposed high speed final drivetrain equipment such as Continuously Variable Transmissions\n(CVTs), sprockets, gears, pulleys, torque converters, clutches, belt drives, clutch drives and\nelectric motors, must be fitted with scatter shields intended to contain drivetrain parts in case of radial failure"
  },
  "T.3.1.8": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.3.1.8",
    "definition": "control, pressurized, electrical components are located below"
  },
  "T.5.2.2": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.2",
    "definition": "The final drivetrain shield must:\na. Be made with solid material (not perforated)\nb. Cover the chain or belt from the drive sprocket to the driven sprocket/chain wheel/belt/pulley\nc. Start and end no higher than parallel to the lowest point of the chain wheel/belt/pulley:\nd. Cover the bottom of the chain or belt or rotating component when fuel, brake lines"
  },
  "T.5.2.3": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.3",
    "definition": "Body panels or other existing covers are acceptable when constructed per T.5.2.7 / T.5.2.8"
  },
  "T.5.2.4": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.4",
    "definition": "Frame Members or existing components that exceed the scatter shield material requirements may be used as part of the shield."
  },
  "T.5.2.5": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.5",
    "definition": "Scatter shields may be composed of multiple pieces. Any gaps must be small (< 3 mm)"
  },
  "T.5.2.6": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.6",
    "definition": "If equipped, the engine drive sprocket cover may be used as part of the scatter shield system."
  },
  "T.5.2.7": {
    "page_number": "66",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.7",
    "definition": "Chain Drive - Scatter shields for chains must:\na. Be made of 2.66 mm (0.105 inch) minimum thickness steel (no alternatives are allowed)"
  }
}

67:
{
  "T.5.2.8": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.8",
    "definition": "Non-metallic Belt Drive - Scatter shields for belts must:\na. Be made from 3.0 mm minimum thickness aluminum alloy 6061-T6\nb. Have a minimum width that is equal to 1.7 times the width of the belt.\nc. Be centered on the center line of the belt\nd. Stay aligned with the belt under all conditions"
  },
  "T.5.2.9": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.9",
    "definition": "Attachment Fasteners - All fasteners attaching scatter shields and guards must be 6 mm or 1/4” minimum diameter Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2"
  },
  "T.5.2.10": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.2.10",
    "definition": "Finger Guards\na. Must cover any drivetrain parts that spin while the vehicle is stationary with the engine\nrunning.\nb. Must be made of material sufficient to resist finger forces.\nc. Mesh or perforated material may be used but must prevent the passage of a 12 mm\ndiameter object through the guard."
  },
  "T.5.3.1": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.3.1",
    "definition": "The rotating part of the Motor(s) EV.4.1 must be contained in a structural casing.\nThe motor casing may be the original motor casing, a team built motor casing or the original\ncasing with additional material added to achieve the minimum required thickness.\n• Minimum thickness for aluminum alloy 6061-T6: 3.0 mm\nIf lower grade aluminum alloy is used, then the material must be thicker to provide an\nequivalent strength.\n• Minimum thickness for steel: 2.0 mm"
  },
  "T.5.3.2": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.3.2",
    "definition": "A Scatter Shield must be included around the Motor(s) when one or both:\n• The motor casing rotates around the stator\n• The motor case is perforated"
  },
  "T.5.3.3": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.3.3",
    "definition": "The Motor Scatter Shield must be:\n• Made from aluminum alloy 6061-T6 or steel\n• Minimum thickness: 1.0 mm"
  },
  "T.5.4.1": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.4.1",
    "definition": "Water cooled engines must use only plain water with no additives of any kind"
  },
  "T.5.4.2": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.4.2",
    "definition": "Liquid coolant for electric motors, Accumulators or HV electronics must be one of:\n• plain water with no additives\n• oil"
  },
  "T.5.4.3": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.4.3",
    "definition": "(EV only) Liquid coolant must not directly touch the cells in the Accumulator"
  },
  "T.5.5.1": {
    "page_number": "67",
    "rule_number": "T.5.5.1",
    "definition": "Any cooling or lubrication system must be sealed to prevent leakage"
  }
}

68:
{
  "T.5.5.2": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.5.2",
    "definition": "The vehicle must be capable of being tilted to a 45° angle without leaking fluid of any type."
  },
  "T.5.5.3": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.5.3",
    "definition": "Flammable liquid and vapors or other leaks must not collect or contact the driver"
  },
  "T.5.5.4": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.5.4",
    "definition": "Two holes of minimum diameter 25 mm each must be provided in the structure or belly pan at\na. The lowest point of the chassis\nb. Rearward of the driver position, forward of a fuel tank or other liquid source\nc. If the lowest point of the chassis obeys T.5.5.4.b, then only one set of holes T.5.5.4.a is\nnecessary"
  },
  "T.5.5.5": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.5.5",
    "definition": "Absorbent material and open collection devices (regardless of material) are prohibited in\ncompartments containing engine, drivetrain, exhaust and fuel systems below the highest\npoint on the exhaust system."
  },
  "T.5.6": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6",
    "definition": "Catch Cans"
  },
  "T.5.6.1": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must have separate containers (catch cans) to retain fluids from any vents from\nthe powertrain systems."
  },
  "T.5.6.2": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6.2",
    "definition": "Catch cans must be:\na. Capable of containing boiling water without deformation\nb. Located rearwards of the Firewall below the driver’s shoulder level\nc. Positively retained, using no tie wraps or tape"
  },
  "T.5.6.3": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6.3",
    "definition": "Catch cans for the engine coolant system and engine lubrication system must have a minimum\ncapacity of 10% of the fluid being contained or 0.9 liter, whichever is higher"
  },
  "T.5.6.4": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6.4",
    "definition": "Catch cans for any vent on other systems containing liquid lubricant or coolant, including a\ndifferential, gearbox, or electric motor, must have a minimum capacity of 10% of the fluid\nbeing contained or 0.5 liter, whichever is higher"
  },
  "T.5.6.5": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.5.6.5",
    "definition": "Any catch can on the cooling system must vent through a hose with a minimum internal\ndiameter of 3 mm down to the bottom levels of the Chassis."
  },
  "T.6": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6",
    "definition": "PRESSURIZED SYSTEMS"
  },
  "T.6.1": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1",
    "definition": "Compressed Gas Cylinders and Lines\nAny system on the vehicle that uses a compressed gas as an actuating medium must meet the\nfollowing:"
  },
  "T.6.1.1": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.1",
    "definition": "Working Gas - The working gas must be non flammable"
  },
  "T.6.1.2": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.2",
    "definition": "Cylinder Certification - The gas cylinder/tank must be commercially manufactured, designed\nand built for the pressure being used, certified by an accredited testing laboratory in the\ncountry of its origin, and labeled or stamped appropriately."
  },
  "T.6.1.3": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.3",
    "definition": "Pressure Regulation - The pressure regulator must be mounted directly onto the gas\ncylinder/tank"
  },
  "T.6.1.4": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.4",
    "definition": "Lines and Fittings - The gas lines and fittings must be appropriate for the maximum possible\noperating pressure of the system."
  },
  "T.6.1.5": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.5",
    "definition": "Insulation - The gas cylinder/tank must be insulated from any heat sources"
  },
  "T.6.1.6": {
    "page_number": "68",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.6",
    "definition": "Cylinder Material – gas cylinders/tanks in a position 150 mm or less from an exhaust system\nmust meet one of the two:\n• Made from metal"
  }
}

69:
{
  "T.6.1.7": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.7",
    "definition": "T.6.1.7 Cylinder Location - The gas cylinder/tank and the pressure regulator must be:\na. Securely mounted inside the Chassis\nb. Located outside of the Cockpit\nc. In a position below the height of the Shoulder Belt Mount T.2.6\nd. Aligned so the axis of the gas cylinder/tank does not point at the driver"
  },
  "T.6.1.8": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.6.1.8",
    "definition": "T.6.1.8 Protection – The gas cylinder/tank and lines must be protected from rollover, collision from any direction, or damage resulting from the failure of rotating equipment"
  },
  "T.6.2.1": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.6.2.1",
    "definition": "T.6.2.1 The driver and anyone standing outside the vehicle must be shielded from any hydraulic pumps and lines with line pressures of 2100 kPa or higher."
  },
  "T.6.2.2": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.6.2.2",
    "definition": "T.6.2.2 The shields must be steel or aluminum with a minimum thickness of 1 mm."
  },
  "T.7.1.1": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.1.1",
    "definition": "T.7.1.1 Aerodynamic Device\nA part on the vehicle which guides airflow for purposes including generation of downforce\nand/or change of drag."
  },
  "T.7.1.2": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.1.2",
    "definition": "T.7.1.2 No power device may be used to move or remove air from under the vehicle. Power ground\neffects are strictly prohibited."
  },
  "T.7.1.3": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.1.3",
    "definition": "T.7.1.3 All Aerodynamic Devices must meet:\na. The mounting system provides sufficient rigidity in the static condition\nb. The Aerodynamic Devices do not oscillate or move excessively when the vehicle is moving. Refer to IN.8.2"
  },
  "T.7.1.4": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.1.4",
    "definition": "T.7.1.4 All forward facing edges that could contact a pedestrian (wings, end plates, and undertrays) must have a minimum radius of 5 mm for all horizontal edges and 3 mm for vertical edges.\nThis may be the radius of the edges themselves, or additional permanently attached pieces\ndesigned to meet this requirement."
  },
  "T.7.1.5": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.1.5",
    "definition": "T.7.1.5 Other edges that a person may touch must not be sharp"
  },
  "T.7.2.1": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.2.1",
    "definition": "T.7.2.1 Conventionally designed Bodywork or a nose cone is not considered an Aerodynamic Device"
  },
  "T.7.2.2": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.2.2",
    "definition": "T.7.2.2 Bodywork, a nose cone, or another component mounted to the vehicle is an Aerodynamic Device if is designed to, or may possibly, produce force due to aerodynamic effects"
  },
  "T.7.2.3": {
    "page_number": "69",
    "rule_number": "T.7.2.3",
    "definition": "T.7.2.3 Bodywork must not contain openings into the cockpit from the front of the vehicle back to the Main Hoop or Firewall. The cockpit opening and minimal openings around the front suspension components are allowed."
  }
}

70:
{
  "T.7.2.4": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.2.4",
    "definition": "All forward facing edges on the Bodywork that could contact people, including the nose, must\nhave forward facing radii minimum 38 mm. This minimum radius must extend 45° or more\nrelative to the forward direction, along the top, sides and bottom of all affected edges."
  },
  "T.7.3.1": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.3.1",
    "definition": "All Aerodynamic Device limitations are measured:\na. With the wheels pointing in the straight ahead position\nb. Without a driver in the vehicle\nThe intent is to standardize the measurement, see GR.6.4.1"
  },
  "T.7.3.2": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.3.2",
    "definition": "Head Restraint Plane\nA transverse vertical plane through the rearmost portion of the front face of the driver head\nrestraint support, excluding any padding, set (if adjustable) in its fully rearward position"
  },
  "T.7.3.3": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.3.3",
    "definition": "Rear Aerodynamic Zone\nThe volume that is:\n• Rearward of the Head Restraint Plane\n• Inboard of two vertical planes parallel to the centerline of the chassis touching the inside\nof the rear tires at the height of the hub centerline"
  },
  "T.7.4": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.4",
    "definition": "Location\nAny part of any Aerodynamic Device or Bodywork must meet V.1.1 and V.1.4.1"
  },
  "T.7.5": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.5",
    "definition": "Length\nIn plan view, any part of any Aerodynamic Device must be:\na. No more than 700 mm forward of the fronts of the front tires\nb. No more than 250 mm rearward of the rear of the rear tires"
  },
  "T.7.6": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.6",
    "definition": "Width\nIn plan view, any part of any Aerodynamic Device must be:"
  },
  "T.7.6.1": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.6.1",
    "definition": "When forward of the centerline of the front wheel axles:\nInboard of two vertical planes parallel to the centerline of the chassis touching the outside of\nthe front tires at the height of the hubs."
  },
  "T.7.6.2": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.6.2",
    "definition": "When between the centerlines of the front and rear wheel axles:\nInboard of a line drawn connecting the outer surfaces of the front and rear tires at the height\nof the wheel centers"
  },
  "T.7.6.3": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.6.3",
    "definition": "When rearward of the centerline of the rear wheel axles:\nIn the Rear Aerodynamic Zone"
  },
  "T.7.7": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.7",
    "definition": "Height"
  },
  "T.7.7.1": {
    "page_number": "70",
    "rule_number": "T.7.7.1",
    "definition": "Any part of any Aerodynamic Device that is located:\na. In the Rear Aerodynamic Zone must be no higher than 1200 mm above the ground\nb. Outside of the Rear Aerodynamic Zone must be no higher than 500 mm above the\nground"
  }
}

71:
{
  "T.7.7.2": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.7.7.2",
    "definition": "T.7.7.2 Bodywork height is not restricted when the Bodywork is located:\n• Between the transverse vertical planes positioned at the front and rear axle centerlines\n• Inside two vertical fore and aft planes 400 mm outboard from the centerline on each\nside of the vehicle"
  },
  "T.8": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8",
    "definition": "T.8 FASTENERS"
  },
  "T.8.1": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.1",
    "definition": "T.8.1 Critical Fasteners\nA fastener (bolt, screw, pin, etc) used in a location specified in the applicable rule"
  },
  "T.8.2": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2",
    "definition": "T.8.2 Critical Fastener Requirements"
  },
  "T.8.2.1": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2.1",
    "definition": "T.8.2.1 Any Critical Fastener must meet, at minimum, one of the following:\na. SAE Grade 5\nb. Metric Class 8.8\nc. AN/MS Specifications\nd. Equivalent to or better than above, as approved by a Rules Question or at Technical\nInspection"
  },
  "T.8.2.2": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2.2",
    "definition": "T.8.2.2 All threaded Critical Fasteners must be one of the following:\n• Hex head\n• Hexagonal recessed drive (Socket Head Cap Screws or Allen screws/bolts)"
  },
  "T.8.2.3": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2.3",
    "definition": "T.8.2.3 All Critical Fasteners must be secured from unintentional loosening with Positive Locking Mechanisms see T.8.3"
  },
  "T.8.2.4": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2.4",
    "definition": "T.8.2.4 A minimum of two full threads must project from any lock nut."
  },
  "T.8.2.5": {
    "page_number": "71",
    "rule_number": "T.8.2.5",
    "definition": "T.8.2.5 Some Critical Fastener applications have additional requirements that are provided in the\napplicable section."
  }
}

72:
{
  "T.8.3": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.8.3",
    "definition": "Positive Locking Mechanisms"
  },
  "T.8.3.1": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.8.3.1",
    "definition": "Positive Locking Mechanisms are defined as those which:\na. Technical Inspectors / team members can see that the device/system is in place (visible).\nb. Do not rely on the clamping force to apply the locking or anti vibration feature.\nMeaning If the fastener begins to loosen, the locking device still prevents the fastener coming\ncompletely loose"
  },
  "T.8.3.2": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.8.3.2",
    "definition": "Examples of acceptable Positive Locking Mechanisms include, but are not limited to:\na. Correctly installed safety wiring\nb. Cotter pins\nc. Nylon lock nuts (where temperature does not exceed 80°C)\nd. Prevailing torque lock nuts\nLock washers, bolts with nylon patches and thread locking compounds (Loctite®), DO NOT\nmeet the positive locking requirement."
  },
  "T.8.4": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.8.4",
    "definition": "Requirements for All Fasteners\nAdjustable tie rod ends must be constrained with a jam nut to prevent loosening."
  },
  "T.9": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9",
    "definition": "ELECTRICAL EQUIPMENT"
  },
  "T.9.1": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.1",
    "definition": "Definitions"
  },
  "T.9.1.1": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.1.1",
    "definition": "High Voltage – HV\nAny voltage more than 60 V DC or 25 V AC RMS"
  },
  "T.9.1.2": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.1.2",
    "definition": "Low Voltage - LV\nAny voltage less than and including 60 V DC or 25 V AC RMS"
  },
  "T.9.1.3": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.1.3",
    "definition": "Normally Open\nA type of electrical relay or contactor that allows current flow only in the energized state"
  },
  "T.9.2": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2",
    "definition": "Low Voltage Batteries"
  },
  "T.9.2.1": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.1",
    "definition": "All Low Voltage Batteries and onboard power supplies must be securely mounted inside the\nChassis below the height of the Shoulder Belt Mount T.2.6"
  },
  "T.9.2.2": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.2",
    "definition": "All Low Voltage batteries must have Overcurrent Protection that trips at or below the\nmaximum specified discharge current of the cells"
  },
  "T.9.2.3": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.3",
    "definition": "The hot (ungrounded) terminal must be insulated."
  },
  "T.9.2.4": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.4",
    "definition": "Any wet cell battery located in the driver compartment must be enclosed in a nonconductive\nmarine type container or equivalent."
  },
  "T.9.2.5": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.5",
    "definition": "Batteries or battery packs based on lithium chemistry must meet one of the two:\na. Have a rigid, sturdy casing made from Nonflammable Material\nb. A commercially available battery designed as an OEM style replacement"
  },
  "T.9.2.6": {
    "page_number": "72",
    "rule_number": "T.9.2.6",
    "definition": "All batteries using chemistries other than lead acid must be presented at Technical Inspection\nwith markings identifying it for comparison to a datasheet or other documentation proving\nthe pack and supporting electronics meet all rules requirements"
  }
}

73:
{
  "T.9.3": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.3",
    "definition": "Master Switches\nEach Master Switch ( IC.9.3 / EV.7.9 ) must meet the following:"
  },
  "T.9.3.1": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.3.1",
    "definition": "Location\na. On the driver’s right hand side of the vehicle\nb. In proximity to the Main Hoop\nc. At the driver's shoulder height\nd. Able to be easily actuated from outside the vehicle"
  },
  "T.9.3.2": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.3.2",
    "definition": "Characteristics\na. Be of the rotary mechanical type\nb. Be rigidly mounted to the vehicle and must not be removed during maintenance\nc. Mounted where the rotary axis of the key is near horizontal and across the vehicle\nd. The ON position must be in the horizontal position and must be marked accordingly\ne. The OFF position must be clearly marked\nf. (EV Only) Operated with a red removable key that must only be removable in the\nelectrically open position"
  },
  "T.9.4": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.4",
    "definition": "Inertia Switch"
  },
  "T.9.4.1": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.4.1",
    "definition": "Inertia Switch Requirement\n• (EV) Must have an Inertia Switch\n• (IC) Should have an Inertia Switch"
  },
  "T.9.4.2": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.4.2",
    "definition": "The Inertia Switch must be:\na. A Sensata Resettable Crash Sensor or equivalent\nb. Mechanically and rigidly attached to the vehicle\nc. Removable to test functionality"
  },
  "T.9.4.3": {
    "page_number": "73",
    "rule_number": "T.9.4.3",
    "definition": "Inertia Switch operation:\na. Must trigger due to a longitudinal impact load which decelerates the vehicle at between\n8 g and 11 g depending on the duration of the deceleration (refer to spec sheet of the\nSensata device)\nb. Must Open the Shutdown Circuit IC.9.2.2 / EV.7.2.2 if triggered\nc. Must latch until manually reset\nd. May be reset by the driver from inside the driver's cell"
  }
}

74:
{
  "VE.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1",
    "definition": "VEHICLE IDENTIFICATION"
  },
  "VE.1.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.1",
    "definition": "Vehicle Number"
  },
  "VE.1.1.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.1.1",
    "definition": "The assigned vehicle number must appear on the vehicle as follows:\na. Locations: in three places, on the front of the chassis and both sides\nb. Height: 150 mm minimum\nc. Font: Block numbers (sans serif characters without italic, outline, shadow, or cursive\nnumbers)\nd. Stroke Width and Spacing between numbers: 18 mm minimum\ne. Color: White numbers on a black background OR black numbers on a white background\nf. Background: round, oval, square or rectangular\ng. Spacing: 25 mm minimum between the edge of the numbers and the edge of the\nbackground\nh. The numbers must not be obscured by parts of the vehicle"
  },
  "VE.1.1.2": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.1.2",
    "definition": "Additional letters or numerals must not show before or after the vehicle number"
  },
  "VE.1.2": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.2",
    "definition": "School Name\nEach vehicle must clearly display the school name.\na. Abbreviations are allowed if unique and generally recognized\nb. The name must be in Roman characters minimum 50 mm high on both sides of the\nvehicle\nc. The characters must be placed on a high contrast background in an easily visible location.\nd. The school name may also appear in non Roman characters, but the Roman character version must be uppermost on the sides."
  },
  "VE.1.3": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.3",
    "definition": "SAE Logo\nThe SAE International Logo must be displayed on the front and/or both sides of the vehicle in\na prominent location."
  },
  "VE.1.4": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.4",
    "definition": "Inspection Sticker\nThe vehicle must have space for the Inspection Sticker(s) IN.13.2 that is:\n• A clear and unobstructed area, minimum 25 cm wide x 20 cm high\n• Located on the upper front surface of the nose along the vehicle centerline"
  },
  "VE.1.5": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.5",
    "definition": "Transponder / RFID Tag"
  },
  "VE.1.5.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.5.1",
    "definition": "Each vehicle must have a functional, properly mounted transponder and/or RFID tag of the\nspecified type(s)"
  },
  "VE.1.5.2": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.1.5.2",
    "definition": "Refer to the Rules FAQ on the FSAE Online website for transponder and RFID tag information\nand mounting details"
  },
  "VE.2": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.2",
    "definition": "VE.2 VEHICLE EQUIPMENT"
  },
  "VE.2.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.1",
    "definition": "Jacking Point"
  },
  "VE.2.1.1": {
    "page_number": "74",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.1.1",
    "definition": "A Jacking Point must be provided at the rear of the vehicle"
  }
}

75:
{
  "VE.2.1.2": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.1.2",
    "definition": "VE.2.1.2 The Jacking Point must be:\n a. Capable of supporting the vehicle weight and of engaging the organizer Quick Jacks\n b. Visible to a person standing 1 m behind the vehicle\n c. Color: Orange\n d. Oriented laterally and perpendicular to the centerline of the vehicle\n e. Made from round, 25 - 30 mm OD aluminum or steel tube\n f. Exposed around the lower 180° of its circumference over a minimum length of 280 mm\n g. Access from the rear of the tube must be unobstructed for 300 mm or more of its length\n h. The height of the tube must allow 75 mm minimum clearance from the bottom of the\n    tube to the ground\n i. When the vehicle is raised to where the bottom of the tube is 200 mm above ground, the\n    wheels do not touch the ground when they are in full rebound"
  },
  "VE.2.2": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.2",
    "definition": "VE.2.2 Push Bar\nEach vehicle must have a removable device which attaches to the rear of the vehicle that:\n a. Allows two people, standing erect behind the vehicle, to push the vehicle around the competition site\n b. Is capable of slowing and stopping the forward motion of the vehicle and pulling it rearwards"
  },
  "VE.2.3.1": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.3.1",
    "definition": "VE.2.3.1 Each team must have two or more fire extinguishers.\n a. One extinguisher must readily be available in the team’s paddock area\n b. One extinguisher must accompany the vehicle when moved using the push bar\n A commercially available on board fire system may be used instead of the fire\n extinguisher that accompanies the vehicle"
  },
  "VE.2.3.2": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.3.2",
    "definition": "VE.2.3.2 Hand held fire extinguishers must NOT be mounted on or in the vehicle"
  },
  "VE.2.3.3": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.3.3",
    "definition": "VE.2.3.3 Each fire extinguisher must meet the following:\n a. Capacity: 0.9 kg (2 lbs)\n b. Working Medium: Dry chemical/dry powder. Aqueous Film Forming Foam (AFFF) and\n Halon extinguishers and systems are prohibited.\n c. Equipped with a manufacturer installed pressure/charge gauge.\n d. Minimum acceptable ratings:\n  • USA, Canada & Brazil: 10BC or 1A 10BC\n  • Europe: 34B or 5A 34B\n  • Australia: 20BE or 1A 10BE\n e. Extinguishers of larger capacity (higher numerical ratings) are acceptable."
  },
  "VE.2.4": {
    "page_number": "75",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.4",
    "definition": "VE.2.4 Electrical Equipment (EV Only)\n The following items must accompany the vehicle at all times:\n • Two pairs of High Voltage insulating gloves\n • A multimeter"
  }
}

76:
{
  "VE.2.5.1": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.5.1",
    "definition": "The mounts for video/photographic cameras must be of a safe and secure design."
  },
  "VE.2.5.2": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.5.2",
    "definition": "All camera installations must be approved at Technical Inspection."
  },
  "VE.2.5.3": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.5.3",
    "definition": "Helmet mounted cameras and helmet camera mounts are prohibited."
  },
  "VE.2.5.4": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.5.4",
    "definition": "The body of a camera or recording unit that weighs more than 0.25 kg must be secured at a minimum of two points on different sides of the camera body."
  },
  "VE.2.5.5": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.2.5.5",
    "definition": "If a tether is used to restrain the camera, the tether length must be limited to prevent contact with the driver."
  },
  "VE.3": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3",
    "definition": "DRIVER EQUIPMENT"
  },
  "VE.3.1": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.1",
    "definition": "General"
  },
  "VE.3.1.1": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.1.1",
    "definition": "Any Driver Equipment:\na. Must be in good condition with no tears, rips, open seams, areas of significant wear,\nabrasions or stains which might compromise performance."
  },
  "VE.3.1.2": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.1.2",
    "definition": "Flame Resistant Material\nFor this section some, but not all, of the approved materials are: Carbon X, Indura, Nomex,\nPolybenzimidazole (common name PBI) and Proban."
  },
  "VE.3.1.3": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.1.3",
    "definition": "Synthetic Material – Prohibited\nShirts, socks or other undergarments (not to be confused with flame resistant underwear)\nmade from nylon or any other synthetic material which could melt when exposed to high heat\nare prohibited."
  },
  "VE.3.1.4": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.1.4",
    "definition": "Officials may impound any non approved Driver Equipment until the end of the competition."
  },
  "VE.3.2": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.2",
    "definition": "Helmet"
  },
  "VE.3.2.1": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.2.1",
    "definition": "The driver must wear a helmet which:\na. Is closed face with an integral, immovable chin guard\nb. Contains an integrated visor/face shield supplied with the helmet\nc. Meets an approved standard\nd. Is properly labeled for that standard"
  },
  "VE.3.2.2": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.2.2",
    "definition": "Acceptable helmet standards are listed below. Any additional approved standards are shown on the Technical Inspection Form or the FAQ on the FSAE Online website.\na. Snell K2010, K2015, K2020, M2010, M2015, M2020, SA2010, SAH2010, SA2015, SA2020\nb. SFI Specs 31.1/2010, 31.1/2015, 41.1/2010, 41.1/2015\nc. FIA Standards FIA 8860-2004, FIA 8860-2010, FIA 8860-2018, FIA 8859-2015"
  },
  "VE.3.3": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3",
    "definition": "Driver Gear"
  },
  "VE.3.3.1": {
    "page_number": "76",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.1",
    "definition": "Driver Suit\nA one piece suit, made from a minimum of two layers of Flame Resistant Material that covers\nthe body from the neck to the ankles and the wrists."
  }
}

77:
{
  "VE.3.3.2": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.2",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.2 Underclothing\nAll competitors should wear fire retardant underwear (long pants and long sleeve shirt) under\ntheir approved Driver Suit."
  },
  "VE.3.3.3": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.3",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.3 Balaclava\nA Balaclava (head sock) which covers the driver’s head, hair and neck, made from Flame Resistant Material"
  },
  "VE.3.3.4": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.4",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.4 Socks\nSocks made from Flame Resistant Material that cover the bare skin between the driver’s suit and the Shoes."
  },
  "VE.3.3.5": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.5",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.5 Shoes\nShoes or boots made from Flame Resistant Material that meet an approved standard and labeled as such:\n• SFI Spec 3.3\n• FIA Standard 8856-2000\n• FIA Standard 8856-2018"
  },
  "VE.3.3.6": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.6",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.6 Gloves\nGloves made from Flame Resistant Material.\nGloves of all leather construction or fire retardant gloves constructed using leather palms with\nno insulating Flame Resistant Material underneath are not acceptable."
  },
  "VE.3.3.7": {
    "page_number": "77",
    "rule_number": "VE.3.3.7",
    "definition": "VE.3.3.7 Arm Restraints\na. Arm restraints must be worn in a way that the driver can release them and exit the\nvehicle unassisted regardless of the vehicle’s position.\nb. Arm restraints must be commercially manufactured. Arm restraints certified to SFI Spec\n3.3 and labeled as such meet this requirement."
  }
}

78:
{
  "IC.1.1.1": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.1.1.1",
    "definition": "The engine(s) used to power the vehicle must:\n a. Be a piston engine(s) using a four stroke primary heat cycle\n b. Have a total combined displacement less than or equal to 710 cc per cycle."
  },
  "IC.1.1.2": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.1.1.2",
    "definition": "Hybrid powertrains, such as those using electric motors running off stored energy, are prohibited."
  },
  "IC.1.1.3": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.1.1.3",
    "definition": "All waste/rejected heat from the primary heat cycle may be used. The method of conversion is not limited to the four stroke cycle."
  },
  "IC.1.1.4": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.1.1.4",
    "definition": "The engine may be modified within the restrictions of the rules."
  },
  "IC.1.2": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.1.2",
    "definition": "Air Intake and Fuel System Location\nAll parts of the engine air system and fuel control, delivery and storage systems (including the throttle or carburetor, and the complete air intake system, including the air cleaner and any air boxes) must lie inside the Tire Surface Envelope F.1.14"
  },
  "IC.2.2.1": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.2.1",
    "definition": "The Intake System must meet IC.1.2"
  },
  "IC.2.2.2": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.2.2",
    "definition": "Any portion of the air intake system that is less than 350 mm above the ground must be shielded from side or rear impacts by structure built per F.6.4 / F.7.5 as applicable."
  },
  "IC.2.3.1": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.3.1",
    "definition": "The intake manifold must be securely attached to the engine block or cylinder head with brackets and mechanical fasteners.\n• Hose clamps, plastic ties, or safety wires do not meet this requirement.\n• The use of rubber bushings or hose is acceptable for creating and sealing air passages,\nbut is not a structural attachment."
  },
  "IC.2.3.2": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.3.2",
    "definition": "Threaded fasteners used to secure and/or seal the intake manifold must have a Positive Locking Mechanism, see T.8.3."
  },
  "IC.2.3.3": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.3.3",
    "definition": "Intake systems with significant mass or cantilever from the cylinder head must be supported to prevent stress to the intake system.\n a. Supports to the engine must be rigid.\n b. Supports to the Chassis must incorporate some isolation to allow for engine movement and chassis flex."
  },
  "IC.2.4.1": {
    "page_number": "78",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.1",
    "definition": "All airflow to the engine(s) must pass through a single circular restrictor placed in the intake system."
  }
}

79:
{
  "IC.2.4.2": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.2",
    "definition": "The only allowed sequence of components are the following:\na. For naturally aspirated engines, the sequence must be: throttle body, restrictor, and\nengine.\nb. For turbocharged or supercharged engines, the sequence must be: restrictor,\ncompressor, throttle body, engine."
  },
  "IC.2.4.3": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.3",
    "definition": "The maximum restrictor diameters at any time during the competition are:\na. Gasoline fueled vehicles 20.0 mm\nb. E85 fueled vehicles 19.0 mm"
  },
  "IC.2.4.4": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.4",
    "definition": "The restrictor must be located to facilitate measurement during Technical Inspection"
  },
  "IC.2.4.5": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.5",
    "definition": "The circular restricting cross section must NOT be movable or flexible in any way"
  },
  "IC.2.4.6": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.4.6",
    "definition": "The restrictor must not be part of the movable portion of a barrel throttle body."
  },
  "IC.2.5.1": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.5.1",
    "definition": "The intake air may be cooled with an intercooler (a charge air cooler).\na. It must be located downstream of the throttle body\nb. Only ambient air may be used to remove heat from the intercooler system\nc. Air to air and water to air intercoolers are permitted\nd. The coolant of a water to air intercooler system must meet T.5.4.1"
  },
  "IC.2.5.2": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.5.2",
    "definition": "If pop-off valves, recirculation valves, or heat exchangers (intercoolers) are used, they must be\npositioned in the intake system as shown in IC.2.4.2.b"
  },
  "IC.2.5.3": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.5.3",
    "definition": "Plenums must not be located anywhere upstream of the throttle body\nFor the purpose of definition, a plenum is any tank or volume that is a significant enlargement\nof the normal intake runner system. Teams may submit their designs via a Rules Question for\nreview prior to competition if the legality of their proposed system is in doubt."
  },
  "IC.2.5.4": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.5.4",
    "definition": "The maximum allowable area of the inner diameter of the intake runner system between the\nrestrictor and throttle body is 2825 mm2"
  },
  "IC.2.6": {
    "page_number": "79",
    "rule_number": "IC.2.6",
    "definition": "Connections to Intake\nAny crankcase or engine lubrication vent lines routed to the intake system must be connected\nupstream of the intake system restrictor."
  }
}

80:
{
  "rule_number_1": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3",
    "definition": "THROTTLE"
  },
  "rule_number_2": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.1",
    "definition": "General"
  },
  "rule_number_3": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.1.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must have a carburetor or throttle body.\na. The carburetor or throttle body may be of any size or design.\nb. Boosted applications must not use carburetors."
  },
  "rule_number_4": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.2",
    "definition": "Throttle Actuation Method\nThe throttle may be actuated:\na. Mechanically by a cable or rod system IC.3.3\nb. By Electronic Throttle Control IC.4"
  },
  "rule_number_5": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.3",
    "definition": "Throttle Actuation – Mechanical\nIC.3.3.1 The throttle cable or rod must:\na. Have smooth operation\nb. Have no possibility of binding or sticking\nc. Be minimum 50 mm from any exhaust system component and out of the exhaust stream\nd. Be protected from being bent or kinked by the driver’s foot when it is operated by the\ndriver or when the driver enters or exits the vehicle\nIC.3.3.2 The throttle actuation system must use two or more return springs located at the throttle\nbody.\nThrottle Position Sensors (TPS) are NOT acceptable as return springs\nIC.3.3.3 Failure of any component of the throttle system must not prevent the throttle returning to\nthe closed position."
  },
  "rule_number_6": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.3.1",
    "definition": "The throttle cable or rod must:\na. Have smooth operation\nb. Have no possibility of binding or sticking\nc. Be minimum 50 mm from any exhaust system component and out of the exhaust stream\nd. Be protected from being bent or kinked by the driver’s foot when it is operated by the\ndriver or when the driver enters or exits the vehicle"
  },
  "rule_number_7": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.3.2",
    "definition": "The throttle actuation system must use two or more return springs located at the throttle\nbody.\nThrottle Position Sensors (TPS) are NOT acceptable as return springs"
  },
  "rule_number_8": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.3.3.3",
    "definition": "Failure of any component of the throttle system must not prevent the throttle returning to\nthe closed position."
  },
  "rule_number_9": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.4",
    "definition": "ELECTRONIC THROTTLE CONTROL\nThis section IC.4 applies only when Electronic Throttle Control is used\nAn Electronic Throttle Control (ETC) system may be used. This is a device or system which\nmay change the engine throttle setting based on various inputs."
  },
  "rule_number_10": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.1",
    "definition": "General Design"
  },
  "rule_number_11": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.1.1",
    "definition": "The electronic throttle must automatically close (return to idle) when power is removed."
  },
  "rule_number_12": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.1.2",
    "definition": "The electronic throttle must use minimum two sources of energy capable of returning the throttle to the idle position.\na. One of the sources may be the device (such as a DC motor) that normally actuates the\nthrottle\nb. The other device(s) must be a throttle return spring that can return the throttle to the\nidle position if loss of actuator power occurs.\nc. Springs in the TPS are not acceptable throttle return springs"
  },
  "rule_number_13": {
    "page_number": "80",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.1.3",
    "definition": "The ETC system may blip the throttle during downshifts when proven that unintended\nacceleration can be avoided. The functional analysis must be documented in the ETC Systems\nForm"
  }
}

81:
{
  "IC.4.2.1": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.2.1",
    "definition": "An ETC system that is commercially available, but does not comply with the regulations, may\nbe used, if approved prior to the event."
  },
  "IC.4.2.2": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.2.2",
    "definition": "To obtain approval, submit a Rules Question which includes:\n• Which ETC system the team is seeking approval to use.\n• The specific ETC rule(s) that the commercial system deviates from.\n• Sufficient technical details of these deviations to determine the acceptability of the\ncommercial system."
  },
  "IC.4.3.1": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.3.1",
    "definition": "The ETC Notice of Intent:\n• Must be submitted to inform the organizer of the intent to run ETC\n• May be used to screen which teams are allowed to use ETC"
  },
  "IC.4.3.2": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.3.2",
    "definition": "The ETC Systems Form must be submitted in order to use ETC"
  },
  "IC.4.3.3": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.3.3",
    "definition": "Submit the ETC Notice of Intent and ETC Systems Form as given in section DR - Document\nRequirements"
  },
  "IC.4.3.4": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.3.4",
    "definition": "Late or non submission will prevent use of ETC, see DR.3.4.1"
  },
  "IC.4.4.1": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.1",
    "definition": "The TPS must measure the position of the throttle or the throttle actuator.\nThrottle position is defined as percent of travel from fully closed to wide open where 0% is\nfully closed and 100% is fully open."
  },
  "IC.4.4.2": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.2",
    "definition": "Two or more separate sensors must be used as TPSs. The TPSs may share the same supply and\nreference lines only if effects of supply and/or reference line voltage offsets can be detected."
  },
  "IC.4.4.3": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.3",
    "definition": "Implausibility is defined as a deviation of more than 10% throttle position between the\nsensors or other failure as defined in Section IC.4. Use of values larger than 10% may be\nconsidered on a case by case basis and require justification in the ETC Systems Form"
  },
  "IC.4.4.4": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.4",
    "definition": "If an Implausibility occurs between the values of the two TPSs and persists for more than 100\nmsec, the power to the electronic throttle must be immediately shut down."
  },
  "IC.4.4.5": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.5",
    "definition": "If three sensors are used, then in the case of a TPS failure, any two TPSs that agree within 10%\nthrottle position may be used to define the throttle position target and the 3rd TPS may be\nignored."
  },
  "IC.4.4.6": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.6",
    "definition": "Each TPS must be able to be checked during Technical Inspection by having one of:\na. A separate detachable connector(s) for any TPS signal(s) to the main ECU without\naffecting any other connections\nb. An inline switchable breakout box available that allows disconnection of each TPS\nsignal(s) to the main ECU without affecting any other connections"
  },
  "IC.4.4.7": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.7",
    "definition": "The TPS signals must be sent directly to the throttle controller using an analogue signal or via\na digital data transmission bus such as CAN or FlexRay. Any failure of the TPSs or TPS wiring\nmust be detectable by the controller and must be treated like Implausibility."
  },
  "IC.4.4.8": {
    "page_number": "81",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.4.8",
    "definition": "When an analogue signal is used, the TPSs will be considered to have failed when they achieve\nan open circuit or short circuit condition which generates a signal outside of the normal\noperating range, for example <0.5 V or >4.5 V."
  }
}

83:
{
  "IC.4.8.2": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.2",
    "definition": "Signals from any sensors must be sent directly to the BSPD. Outputs from other modules may not be used in place of the raw sensor signals."
  },
  "IC.4.8.3": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.3",
    "definition": "The BSPD must monitor for the following conditions:\\na. Both of the following for more than one second:\\n• Demand for Hard Braking IC.4.6\\n• Throttle more than 10% open IC.4.4\\nb. Loss of signal from the braking sensor(s) for more than 100 msec\\nc. Loss of signal from the throttle sensor(s) for more than 100 msec\\nd. Removal of power from the BSPD circuit"
  },
  "IC.4.8.4": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.4",
    "definition": "When any of the above conditions exist, the BSPD must Open the Shutdown Circuit IC.9.2.2"
  },
  "IC.4.8.5": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.5",
    "definition": "The BSPD must only be reset by cycling the Primary Master Switch IC.9.3 OFF and ON"
  },
  "IC.4.8.6": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.6",
    "definition": "The BSPD must not reset when the Cockpit Main Switch IC.9.4 is turned OFF"
  },
  "IC.4.8.7": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.4.8.7",
    "definition": "The BSPD signals and function must be able to be checked during Technical Inspection by having one of:\\na. A separate set of detachable connectors for any signals from the braking sensor(s),\\nthrottle sensor(s) and removal of power to only the BSPD device.\\nb. An inline switchable breakout box available that allows disconnection of the brake\\nsensor(s), throttle sensor(s) individually and power to only the BSPD device."
  },
  "IC.5": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5",
    "definition": ""
  },
  "IC.5.1": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.1",
    "definition": ""
  },
  "IC.5.1.1": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.1.1",
    "definition": "Vehicles must be operated with the fuels provided by the organizer at the competition."
  },
  "IC.5.1.2": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.1.2",
    "definition": "Fuels provided are expected to be Gasoline and E85. Consult the individual competition websites for fuel specifics and other information."
  },
  "IC.5.1.3": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.1.3",
    "definition": "No agents other than the provided fuel and air may go into the combustion chamber."
  },
  "IC.5.2": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.2",
    "definition": ""
  },
  "IC.5.2.1": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.2.1",
    "definition": "The Fuel System must meet the following design criteria:\\n a. The Fuel Tank is capable of being filled to capacity without manipulating the tank or the vehicle in any manner.\\n b. During refueling on a level surface, the formation of air cavities or other effects that cause the fuel level observed at the sight tube to drop after movement or operation of the vehicle (other than due to consumption) are prevented.\\n c. Spillage during refueling cannot contact the driver position, exhaust system, hot engine parts, or the ignition system."
  },
  "IC.5.2.2": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.2.2",
    "definition": "The Fuel System location must meet IC.1.2 and F.9"
  },
  "IC.5.2.3": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.2.3",
    "definition": "A Firewall must separate the Fuel Tank from the driver, per T.1.8"
  },
  "IC.5.3": {
    "page_number": "83",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3",
    "definition": "The part(s) of the fuel containment device that is in contact with the fuel."
  }
}

84:
{
  "IC.5.3.1": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3.1",
    "definition": "Fuel Tanks made of a rigid material must:\na. Be securely attached to the vehicle structure. The mounting method must not allow\nchassis flex to load the Fuel Tank.\nb. Not be used to carry any structural loads; from Roll Hoops, suspension, engine or\ngearbox mounts"
  },
  "IC.5.3.2": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3.2",
    "definition": "Any Fuel Tank that is made from a flexible material, for example a bladder fuel cell or a bag tank:\na. Must be enclosed inside a rigid fuel tank container which is securely attached to the vehicle structure.\nb. The Fuel Tank container may be load carrying"
  },
  "IC.5.3.3": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3.3",
    "definition": "Any size Fuel Tank may be used."
  },
  "IC.5.3.4": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3.4",
    "definition": "The Fuel Tank, by design, must not have a variable capacity."
  },
  "IC.5.3.5": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.3.5",
    "definition": "The Fuel System must have a provision for emptying the Fuel Tank if required."
  },
  "IC.5.4.1": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.1",
    "definition": "All Fuel Tanks must have a Fuel Filler Neck which must be:\na. Minimum 35 mm inner diameter at any point between the Fuel Tank and the Fuel Filler cap"
  },
  "IC.5.4.2": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.2",
    "definition": "The portion of the Fuel Filler Neck nearest to the Fuel Filler cap must be:\na. Minimum 125 mm vertical height above the top level of the Fuel Tank\nb. Angled no more than 30° from the vertical"
  },
  "IC.5.4.3": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.3",
    "definition": "The Fuel Filler Neck must be accompanied by a clear fuel resistant sight tube for reading the fuel level which must be:\na. Visible vertical height: 125 mm minimum\nb. Inside diameter: 6 mm minimum\nc. Above the top surface of the Fuel Tank"
  },
  "IC.5.4.4": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.4",
    "definition": "A clear Fuel Filler Neck tube may be used as a sight tube, subject to approval by a Rules Question or technical inspectors at the event."
  },
  "IC.5.4.5": {
    "page_number": "84",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.5",
    "definition": "Fuel Level Line - A permanent, non movable fuel level line must be located between 12 mm and 25 mm below the top of the visible portion of the sight tube."
  }
}

85:
{
  "IC.5": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5",
    "definition": "Fuel Tank Filling"
  },
  "IC.5.4.6": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.6",
    "definition": "The sight tube and fuel level line must be clearly visible to two individuals (one to fill the tank,\nthe other to visually verify fill) without the need of assistance (artificial lighting, magnifiers,\netc) or the need to remove any parts (body panels, etc)."
  },
  "IC.5.4.7": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.7",
    "definition": "The individual filling the tank must have complete direct access to the filler neck opening with\na standard two gallon gas can assembly.\nThe gas can is minimum 25 cm wide x 25 cm deep x 35 cm high, with a 25 cm spout at the top"
  },
  "IC.5.4.8": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.4.8",
    "definition": "The filler neck must have a fuel cap that can withstand severe vibrations or high pressures\nsuch as could occur during a vehicle rollover event"
  },
  "IC.5.5": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.5",
    "definition": "Fuel Tank Filling"
  },
  "IC.5.5.1": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.5.1",
    "definition": "Fueling / Refueling policies and procedures are at the discretion of the fuel crew and officials."
  },
  "IC.5.5.2": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.5.2",
    "definition": "The tank will be filled to the fill line, or if a filling system is used, to the automatic stop point."
  },
  "IC.5.5.3": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.5.3",
    "definition": "If, for any reason, the fuel level changes after the team have moved the vehicle, then no additional fuel will be added, unless fueling after Endurance, see D.13.2.5"
  },
  "IC.5.6": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.6",
    "definition": "Venting Systems"
  },
  "IC.5.6.1": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.6.1",
    "definition": "Venting systems for the fuel tank and fuel delivery system must not allow fuel to spill during hard cornering or acceleration."
  },
  "IC.5.6.2": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.6.2",
    "definition": "All fuel vent lines must have a check valve to prevent fuel leakage when the tank is inverted."
  },
  "IC.5.6.3": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.6.3",
    "definition": "All fuel vent lines must exit outside the bodywork."
  },
  "IC.5.7": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7",
    "definition": "Fuel Lines"
  },
  "IC.5.7.1": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7.1",
    "definition": "Fuel lines must be securely attached to the vehicle and/or engine."
  },
  "IC.5.7.2": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7.2",
    "definition": "All fuel lines must be shielded from possible rotating equipment failure or collision damage."
  },
  "IC.5.7.3": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7.3",
    "definition": "Plastic fuel lines between the fuel tank and the engine (supply and return) are prohibited."
  },
  "IC.5.7.4": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7.4",
    "definition": "Any rubber fuel line or hose used must meet the following:\na. The components over which the hose is clamped must have annular bulb or barbed fittings to retain the hose\nb. Clamps specifically designed for fuel lines must be used.\nThese clamps have three features: a full 360° wrap, a nut and bolt system for tightening,\nand rolled edges to prevent the clamp cutting into the hose"
  },
  "IC.5.7.5": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.5.7.5",
    "definition": "Worm gear type hose clamps must not be used on any fuel line."
  },
  "IC.6": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.6",
    "definition": "FUEL INJECTION"
  },
  "IC.6.1": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.1",
    "definition": "Low Pressure Injection (LPI)\nLow Pressure fuel injection systems are those functioning at a pressure below 10 Bar. Most\nPort Fuel Injected (PFI) fuel systems are low pressure."
  },
  "IC.6.1.1": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.1.1",
    "definition": "Any Low Pressure flexible fuel lines must be one of:\n• Metal braided hose with threaded fittings (crimped on or reusable)\n• Reinforced rubber hose with some form of abrasion resistant protection"
  },
  "IC.6.1.2": {
    "page_number": "85",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.1.2",
    "definition": "Fuel rail and mounting requirements:"
  }
}

86:
{
  "IC.6.2.1": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.1",
    "definition": "Definitions\na. High Pressure fuel systems - those functioning at 10 Bar pressure or above\nb. Direct Injection fuel systems - where the injection occurs directly into the combustion system\nDirect Injection systems often utilize a low pressure electric fuel pump and high pressure\nmechanical “boost” pump driven off the engine.\nc. High Pressure Fuel Lines - those between the boost pump and injectors\nd. Low Pressure Fuel Lines - from the electric supply pump to the boost pump"
  },
  "IC.6.2.2": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.2",
    "definition": "All High Pressure Fuel Lines must:\na. Be stainless steel rigid line or Aeroquip FC807 smooth bore PTFE hose with stainless steel reinforcement and visible Nomex tracer yarn. Equivalent products may be used with prior approval.\nb. Not incorporate elastomeric seals\nc. Be rigidly connected every 100 mm by mechanical fasteners to structural engine components such as cylinder heads or block"
  },
  "IC.6.2.3": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.3",
    "definition": "Any Low Pressure flexible Fuel Lines must be one of:\n• Metal braided hose with threaded fittings (crimped on or reusable)\n• Reinforced rubber hose with some form of abrasion resistant protection"
  },
  "IC.6.2.4": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.4",
    "definition": "Fuel rail mounting requirements:\na. The fuel rail must be securely attached to the engine block or cylinder head with brackets\nand mechanical fasteners. Hose clamps, plastic ties, or safety wires do not meet this\nrequirement.\nb. The fastening method must be sufficient to hold the fuel rail in place with the maximum\nregulated pressure acting on the injector internals and neglecting any assistance from\ncylinder pressure acting on the injector tip.\nc. Threaded fasteners used to secure the fuel rail are Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2"
  },
  "IC.6.2.5": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.5",
    "definition": "High Pressure Fuel Pump – must be rigidly mounted to structural engine components such as\nthe cylinder head or engine block."
  },
  "IC.6.2.6": {
    "page_number": "86",
    "rule_number": "IC.6.2.6",
    "definition": "Pressure Regulator – must be fitted between the High Pressure and Low Pressure sides of the\nfuel system in parallel with the DI boost pump. The external regulator must be used even if\nthe DI boost pump comes equipped with an internal regulator."
  }
}

87:
{
  "IC.7": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7",
    "definition": "EXHAUST AND NOISE CONTROL"
  },
  "IC.7.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.1",
    "definition": "EXHAUST PROTECTION\nThe exhaust system must be separated from any of the following components by means given\nin T.1.6.3:\na. Flammable materials, including the fuel and fuel system, the oil and oil system\nb. Thermally sensitive components, including brake lines, composite materials, and\nbatteries"
  },
  "IC.7.1.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.1.1",
    "definition": "The exhaust system must be separated from any of the following components by means given\nin T.1.6.3:\na. Flammable materials, including the fuel and fuel system, the oil and oil system\nb. Thermally sensitive components, including brake lines, composite materials, and\nbatteries"
  },
  "IC.7.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.2",
    "definition": "EXHAUST OUTLET\nThe exhaust must be routed to prevent the driver from fumes at any speed considering the\ndraft of the vehicle"
  },
  "IC.7.2.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.2.1",
    "definition": "The exhaust must be routed to prevent the driver from fumes at any speed considering the\ndraft of the vehicle"
  },
  "IC.7.2.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.2.2",
    "definition": "EXHAUST OUTLET(S) must be:\na. No more than 45 cm aft of the centerline of the rear axle\nb. No more than 60 cm above the ground."
  },
  "IC.7.2.3": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.2.3",
    "definition": "Any exhaust components (headers, mufflers, etc.) that protrude from the side of the body in\nfront of the Main Hoop must be shielded to prevent contact by persons approaching the\nvehicle or a driver exiting the vehicle"
  },
  "IC.7.2.4": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.2.4",
    "definition": "Fibrous/absorbent material, (such as header wrap), must not be used on the outside of an\nexhaust manifold or exhaust system."
  },
  "IC.7.3": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.3",
    "definition": "Variable Exhaust"
  },
  "IC.7.3.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.3.1",
    "definition": "Adjustable tuning or throttling devices are permitted."
  },
  "IC.7.3.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.3.2",
    "definition": "Manually adjustable tuning devices must require tools to change"
  },
  "IC.7.3.3": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.3.3",
    "definition": "Refer to IN.10.2 for additional requirements during the Noise Test"
  },
  "IC.7.4": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.4",
    "definition": "Connections to Exhaust\nCrankcase breathers that pass through the oil catch tank(s) to exhaust systems, or vacuum\ndevices that connect directly to the exhaust system, are prohibited."
  },
  "IC.7.5": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.5",
    "definition": "NOISE LEVEL AND TESTING\nThe vehicle must stay below the permitted sound level at all times IN.10.5"
  },
  "IC.7.5.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.5.1",
    "definition": "The vehicle must stay below the permitted sound level at all times IN.10.5"
  },
  "IC.7.5.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.7.5.2",
    "definition": "Sound level will be verified during Technical Inspection, refer to IN.10"
  },
  "IC.8": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8",
    "definition": "ELECTRICAL"
  },
  "IC.8.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8.1",
    "definition": "STARTER\nEach vehicle must start the engine using an onboard starter at all times"
  },
  "IC.8.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8.2",
    "definition": "BATTERIES\nRefer to T.9.2 for specific requirements of Low Voltage batteries"
  },
  "IC.8.3": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8.3",
    "definition": "VOLTAGE LIMIT"
  },
  "IC.8.3.1": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8.3.1",
    "definition": "Voltage between any two electrical connections must be Low Voltage T.9.1.2"
  },
  "IC.8.3.2": {
    "page_number": "87",
    "rule_number": "IC.8.3.2",
    "definition": "This voltage limit does not apply to the following systems:\n• High Voltage systems for ignition\n• High Voltage systems for injectors"
  }
}

88:
{
  "IC.9": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9",
    "definition": "SHUTDOWN SYSTEM"
  },
  "IC.9.1": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.1",
    "definition": "Shutdown Circuit"
  },
  "IC.9.1.1": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.1.1",
    "definition": "The Shutdown Circuit consists of the following components:\na. Primary Master Switch IC.9.3\nb. Cockpit Main Switch IC.9.4\nc. (ETC Only) Brake System Plausibility Device (BSPD) IC.4.8\nd. Brake Overtravel Switch (BOTS) T.3.3\ne. Inertia Switch (if used) T.9.4"
  },
  "IC.9.1.2": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.1.2",
    "definition": "The team must be able to demonstrate all features and functions of the Shutdown Circuit and components at Technical Inspection"
  },
  "IC.9.1.3": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.1.3",
    "definition": "The international electrical symbol (a red spark on a white edged blue triangle) must be near both the Primary Master Switch and Cockpit Main Switch."
  },
  "IC.9.2": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.2",
    "definition": "Shutdown Circuit Operation"
  },
  "IC.9.2.1": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.2.1",
    "definition": "The Shutdown Circuit must Open upon operation of, or detection from any of the components listed in IC.9.1.1"
  },
  "IC.9.2.2": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.2.2",
    "definition": "When the Shutdown Circuit Opens, it must:\na. Stop the engine\nb. Disconnect power to the:\n• Fuel Pump(s)\n• Ignition\n• (ETC only) Electronic Throttle IC.4.1.1"
  },
  "IC.9.3": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.3",
    "definition": "Primary Master Switch"
  },
  "IC.9.3.1": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.3.1",
    "definition": "Configuration and Location - The Primary Master Switch must meet T.9.3"
  },
  "IC.9.3.2": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.3.2",
    "definition": "Function - the Primary Master Switch must:\na. Disconnect power to ALL electrical circuits, including the battery, alternator, lights, fuel pump(s), ignition and electrical controls.\nAll battery current must flow through this switch\nb. Be direct acting, not act through a relay or logic."
  },
  "IC.9.4": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.4",
    "definition": "Cockpit Main Switch"
  },
  "IC.9.4.1": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.4.1",
    "definition": "Configuration - The Cockpit Main Switch must:\na. Be a push-pull or push-rotate emergency switch (pushing the button is the OFF position)\nb. Have a diameter of 24 mm minimum"
  },
  "IC.9.4.2": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.4.2",
    "definition": "Location – The Cockpit Main Switch must be:\na. In easy reach of the driver when in a normal driving position wearing Harness\nb. Adjacent to the Steering Wheel\nc. Unobstructed by the Steering Wheel or any other part of the vehicle"
  },
  "IC.9.4.3": {
    "page_number": "88",
    "rule_number": "IC.9.4.3",
    "definition": "Function - the Cockpit Main Switch may act through a relay"
  }
}

89:
{
  "EV.1.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.1.1",
    "definition": "Tractive System – TS\nEvery part electrically connected to the Motor(s) and/or Accumulator(s)\n"
  },
  "EV.1.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.1.2",
    "definition": "Grounded Low Voltage - GLV\nEvery electrical part that is not part of the Tractive System\n"
  },
  "EV.1.3": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.1.3",
    "definition": "Accumulator\nAll the battery cells or super capacitors that store the electrical energy to be used by the\nTractive System\n"
  },
  "EV.2.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.2.1",
    "definition": "Electrical System Form - ESF"
  },
  "EV.2.1.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.2.1.1",
    "definition": "Each team must submit an Electrical System Form (ESF) with a clearly structured\ndocumentation of the entire vehicle electrical system (including control and Tractive System)."
  },
  "EV.2.1.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.2.1.2",
    "definition": "The ESF may provide guidance or more details than the Formula SAE Rules."
  },
  "EV.2.1.3": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.2.1.3",
    "definition": "Use the format provided and submit the ESF as given in section DR - Document Requirements"
  },
  "EV.2.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.2.2",
    "definition": "Submission Penalties\nPenalties for the ESF are imposed as given in section DR - Document Requirements."
  },
  "EV.3.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.1",
    "definition": "Operation"
  },
  "EV.3.1.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.1.1",
    "definition": "Supplying power to the motor to drive the vehicle in reverse is prohibited"
  },
  "EV.3.1.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.1.2",
    "definition": "Drive by wire control of wheel torque is permitted"
  },
  "EV.3.1.3": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.1.3",
    "definition": "Any algorithm or electronic control unit that can adjust the requested wheel torque may only\ndecrease the total driver requested torque and must not increase it"
  },
  "EV.3.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.2",
    "definition": "Energy Meter"
  },
  "EV.3.2.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.2.1",
    "definition": "All Electric Vehicles must run with the Energy Meter provided by the organizer\nRefer to the FSAEOnline Website AD.2.2 for detail information on the Energy Meter"
  },
  "EV.3.2.2": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.2.2",
    "definition": "The Energy Meter must be installed in an easily accessible location"
  },
  "EV.3.2.3": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.2.3",
    "definition": "All Tractive System power must flow through the Energy Meter"
  },
  "EV.3.2.4": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.2.4",
    "definition": "Power and Voltage limits will be checked by the Energy Meter data\nEnergy is calculated as the time integrated value of the measured voltage multiplied by the\nmeasured current logged by the Energy Meter."
  },
  "EV.3.3": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.3",
    "definition": "Power and Voltage"
  },
  "EV.3.3.1": {
    "page_number": "89",
    "rule_number": "EV.3.3.1",
    "definition": "The maximum power measured by the Energy Meter must not exceed 80 kW"
  }
}

90:
{
  "Lookup Table for Rules": {
